'''Alpheus Spring Packard, Jr.''', LL.D. (February 19, 1839 – February 14, 1905) was an [[United States|American]] [[entomologist]] and [[palaeontologist]]. He described over 500 new animal species – especially butterflies and moths – and was one of the founders of ''[[The American Naturalist]]''.<ref name="Cockerell">Cockerell (1920)</ref>

==Biography==
He was the son of [[Alpheus Spring Packard, Sr.]] (1798–1884) and the brother of [[William Alfred Packard]].  He was born in [[Brunswick, Maine|Brunswick]], [[Maine]] and was Professor of [[Zoology]] and [[Geology]] at [[Brown University]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]] from 1878 until his death. He was a vocal proponent of Neo-[[Lamarckism]] during the [[eclipse of Darwinism]].<ref name="Sorenson">Sorenson (1995)</ref>

His chief work was the classification and anatomy of [[arthropod]]s, and contributions to economic [[entomology]], [[zoogeography]], and the [[phylogeny]] and metamorphoses of [[insect]]s. Packard was appointed to the [[United States Entomological Commission]] in 1877 where he served with [[Charles Valentine Riley]] and [[Cyrus Thomas]].<ref name="Mallis">Mallis (1971)</ref> He wrote school textbooks, such as ''Zoölogy for High Schools and Colleges'' (eleventh edition, 1904).  His ''Monograph of the Bombycine Moths of North America'' was published in three parts (1895, 1905, 1915, edited by T. D. A. Cockerell).

He died on February 14, 1905.

==Writings by A. S. Packard Jr.==
{{wikisource author}}
* ''Report on the insects collected on the Penobscot and Alleguash Rivers, during August and September, 1861, Sixth Annual Report of the Secretary of the Maine Board of Agriculture, Augusta, Maine (pp. 373-376)'' (1861)
* ''Guide to the Study of Insects'' (1869; third edition, 1872)
* ''[https://archive.org/details/mammothcaveandi01putngoog The Mammoth Cave and its Inhabitants]'' (1872), with F. W. Putnam
* ''Life-History of Animals'' (1876)
* ''A Naturalist on the Labrador Coast'' (1891)
* [https://archive.org/details/lamarckfounderof00pack ''Lamarck, the Founder of Evolution: His Life and Work''] (1901), French translation, 1903.

