{{Chinese name|[[Wu (surname)|Wu]]}}
[[File:Wu Jie 2010 Somalia stamp.jpg|thumb|Wu Jie]]

'''Wu Jie''' ({{zh|s=吴杰|t=吳杰|p=Wú Jié}}; born October 1963) is a [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] military [[aviator|pilot]] and [[astronaut]] selected as part of the [[Shenzhou spacecraft|Shenzhou program]].

==Biography==
Wu Jie was born in [[Zhengzhou]], [[Henan]] province, [[China]]. In 1987 he graduated from the [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] (PLAAF) Engineering College and later the PLAAF Flight College. A [[fighter aircraft|fighter]] pilot in the PLAAF, he had accumulated 1100 flight-hours.

In November 1996, he and [[Li Qinglong]], started training at the [[Russia]]n [[Yuri Gagarin Cosmonauts Training Center]]. When they returned to China a year later, they acted as the trainers for the first group of Shenzhou astronauts. Before the flight of ''[[Shenzhou 5]]'' it was thought that he or Li Qinglong would fly the mission, that was eventually flown by [[Yang Liwei]].

Wu was then one of the six astronauts in the final training for ''[[Shenzhou 6]]''.

