{{nihongo|'''Yoshio Abe'''|阿部 余四男|Abe Yoshio|extra=1891–1960|lead=yes}} was a [[professor]] of [[zoology]] at [[Karahuto Normal University]].

He was the first Japanese scientist to study [[Kinorhyncha|kinorhynchs]], and one such animal, ''Dracoderes abei'',  was named after him.<ref>Behlens, Bo, Watkins, Michael. and  Grayson, Michael ''Eponym Dictionary of Mammals'', Johns Hopkins University Press, 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-801893-04-9}}. p. 1</ref> Also named after him was [[Sakhalin myotis|Abe's Whiskered Bat]], ''Myotis abei'' Yoshikura 1944, as a tribute from one of his students.

